          <h2>How the South Carolina income tax calculator works</h2>
          <p>
            This tool estimates your South Carolina state income tax using a progressive bracket system. You enter your
            annual gross income, filing status, and optional deductions/credits. The calculator:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>Subtracts pre-tax deductions to get adjusted income.</li>
            <li>Subtracts either the South Carolina standard deduction (approximation) or your itemized deductions.</li>
            <li>Applies the SC tax brackets for your filing status to compute state income tax.</li>
            <li>Subtracts any South Carolina tax credits you enter.</li>
            <li>Optionally applies a local income tax rate you specify.</li>
            <li>Computes your effective tax rate and estimated take-home pay per year and per paycheck.</li>
          </ol>

          <h3>South Carolina progressive tax brackets (conceptual)</h3>
          <p>
            South Carolina uses a progressive income tax. That means different portions of your income are taxed at
            different rates. A simplified example of how brackets work:
          </p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm">
              Taxable income = Gross income − Pre-tax deductions − Standard/Itemized deductions
            </p>
            <p class="font-mono text-sm mt-2">
              SC tax = (Income in bracket 1 × rate 1) + (Income in bracket 2 × rate 2) + … + (Income in top bracket × top rate)
            </p>
          </div>
          <p>
            Your <strong>marginal rate</strong> is the rate that applies to your last dollar of income. Your
            <strong>effective rate</strong> is total tax divided by total income, which is always lower than the top
            marginal rate because lower portions of your income are taxed at lower rates.
          </p>

          <h2>Step-by-step: using the South Carolina income tax calculator</h2>
          <h3>1. Choose your tax year and filing status</h3>
          <p>
            Select the tax year (2024 or 2023) and your filing status. Brackets and standard deductions can differ by
            year and status, so this choice affects your estimate.
          </p>

          <h3>2. Enter your annual gross income</h3>
          <p>
            Use your expected total income for the year before any deductions:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Wages and salary (from your W‑2).</li>
            <li>Self-employment or freelance income.</li>
            <li>Taxable interest, dividends, and other income.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>3. Add optional adjustments</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pre-tax deductions</strong> – retirement contributions, HSA, or other amounts excluded from taxable income.</li>
            <li><strong>Itemized deductions</strong> – if your South Carolina itemized deductions exceed the standard deduction.</li>
            <li><strong>SC tax credits</strong> – for example, credits for child/dependent care, education, or other state programs.</li>
            <li><strong>Local income tax rate</strong> – most South Carolina taxpayers can leave this at 0%.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>4. Review your results</h3>
          <p>The calculator shows:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>SC state income tax</strong> – your estimated annual liability after credits.</li>
            <li><strong>Effective SC tax rate</strong> – tax as a percentage of your gross income.</li>
            <li><strong>Net take-home pay</strong> – after state and local income tax.</li>
            <li><strong>Per-paycheck amounts</strong> – based on your chosen pay frequency.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>This calculator focuses on <strong>South Carolina state income tax</strong> only.</li>
            <li>It does <strong>not</strong> compute federal income tax, Social Security, or Medicare.</li>
            <li>It uses reasonable approximations for standard deductions and brackets; actual law may change each year.</li>
            <li>Special rules for retirees, military, business owners, and certain credits are not fully modeled.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For official guidance, forms, and the latest bracket thresholds, always refer to the
            <a href="https://dor.sc.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">South Carolina Department of Revenue</a>
            and, if needed, consult a qualified tax professional.
          </p>

          <h2>FAQ: South Carolina income tax</h2>

          <h3>Does South Carolina tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
          <p>
            No. South Carolina does not tax Social Security retirement benefits. Many retirees also qualify for
            additional deductions on other retirement income, which can significantly reduce their state tax bill.
          </p>

          <h3>Is South Carolina a high-tax or low-tax state?</h3>
          <p>
            South Carolina’s top marginal income tax rate is moderate compared with other states, and property taxes are
            relatively low. However, the overall burden depends on your income mix, property ownership, and spending
            patterns (because of sales and local taxes).
          </p>

          <h3>How often are South Carolina tax brackets updated?</h3>
          <p>
            South Carolina generally adjusts its income tax brackets annually for inflation. The calculator is designed
            to use current-year thresholds, but you should confirm details with official state resources if you are
            planning major financial decisions.
          </p>

          <h3>Can this calculator replace professional tax advice?</h3>
          <p>
            No. This tool is for educational and planning purposes only. It simplifies many aspects of the South
            Carolina tax code and may not capture all deductions, credits, or special situations that apply to you.
          </p>
